observations.recommendation:
1.11	We recommended to the Local Chief Executive the following:
1.11.1	Require the City Treasurer to request the depository bank to provide the agency with the copy of the bank statements on time, within five days after the end of the month. If not possible, request electronic copies (snapshots) of the transactions of the bank accounts to facilitate the immediate preparation of the monthly BRS report or enroll in the WE access for easy retrieval of copies;
2. Direct the City Accountant to prepare and submit monthly BRS within the prescribed period for review so that errors/omissions and/or reconciling items would be immediately detected for correction and adjustment in the books of accounts, thus ensuring the accuracy and reliability of the Cash in Bank balances in the agency’s trial balance and financial statements;
3. If possible, record the monthly/quarterly interest earned due for each bank account in the agency-appropriate books to arrive at an accurate balance of Cash in Bank; and
4. Instruct the City Accountant to evaluate the efficiency and directly supervise the work output of its personnel and staff and ensure that their duties and responsibilities are carried out in a timely manner in order not to cause significant delays in its accounting and reporting functions.

2.12	We recommended to the Local Chief Executive the following:
2.12.1	Require the General Services Office to complete the Annual Physical Inventory Count and update the records of the Report on Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment;
2.12.2	Coordinate with the City Accounting Department to reconcile the discrepancies between the accounting records and RPCPPE;
2.12.3	Investigate the causes of the discrepancies and require explanations from the person responsible; and
2.12.4	Require the City Accountant to record adjustments after completion of proper reconciliation with GSO.

3.17	We recommended to the Local Chief Executive to:
3.17.1	Require the City Accounting Department to ensure that the recording and recognition of Accounts Payable are fully supported with complete documentation;
Prepare a Journal Entry Voucher to recognize the Accounts Payable pertaining to the outstanding/served POs, to adjust the understatement of the accounts payable and the corresponding asset accounts;
Conduct a thorough review of accounts payable outstanding for more than two (2) years:
Adhere to COA-DBM Joint Circular No. 1 s. 2021 dated March 8, 2021, and Section 98 of Presidential Decree No. 1445;
Provide supporting documents to substantiate the validity of accounts payables (e.g., actual claims, perfected contracts, and/or other supporting documents);
Revert to the Accumulated Surplus/ Deficit account payables with no valid claims;
3.17.2	Conduct a regular accounts payable reconciliation and monitoring between the General Services Office’s (GSO) records;
3.17.3	Direct the General Services Department to ensure that proper coordination and communication are made in a prompt manner to enable the CAD to properly record and recognize completed and served Purchase Orders (POs); and
3.17.4	Require that complete documentation (e.g., Acceptance and Inspection Reports, Delivery Receipts, Invoices, etc.) for delivered goods and rendered services are transmitted to the City Accounting Department (CAD) for timely recognition.

4.13	We recommended that the Local Chief Executive to:
4.13.1	Direct the City Accounting Department (CAD) to reclassify the Loans Payable-Domestic account in the Statement of Financial Position, properly segregating it into current and non-current portions in accordance with IPSAS No. 1. Specifically, the current portion of the Land Bank of the Philippines loan amounting to ₱33,657,013.10 should be presented as a current liability;
4.13.2	Instruct the CAD to immediately coordinate with the National Housing Authority (NHA) to obtain an updated Statement of Account as of December 31, 2024, and perform a detailed reconciliation with the LGU's subsidiary ledgers for the Gingoog Housing Projects Phase 1 and Phase 2 loans. This reconciliation should identify and explain all discrepancies;
4.13.3	Require the CAD to prepare adjusting journal entries to correct the overstatement of the NHA loans by ₱2,750,000.00 and to reclassify the loan payments of ₱1,000,000.00 incorrectly charged to Other Maintenance and Operating Expenses to the Loans Payable-Domestic account;
4.13.4	Direct the CAD to determine the repayment terms of the NHA loans to accurately classify the outstanding balance into current and non-current portions in the Statement of Financial Position;
4.13.5	Implement a policy of regular reconciliation of all loan accounts with the respective lending institutions to ensure the accuracy and completeness of loan records; and
4.13.6	Strengthen internal controls over the recording of loan transactions, ensuring that all loan proceeds, payments, and interest expenses are properly recorded in the correct accounts and periods.

5.12	We recommended that the Local Chief Executive to:
5.12.1	Direct the City Treasurer’s Office (CTO) to immediately prepare and submit a corrected and reconciled Summary of Delinquent Taxable Real Properties as of December 31, 2024, ensuring accuracy in all computations, barangay assignments, and overall totals. This should be submitted within ten (10) calendar days from receipt of this memorandum;
5.12.2	Require the CTO and the City Accounting Department (CAD) to conduct a thorough reconciliation of the beginning balances of RPT and SET Receivables for CY 2024 with the Certified List of Taxable Real Properties, strictly adhering to the requirements of Section 20, Chapter 3 of the NGAS for LGUs Volume I. This reconciliation should be completed within fifteen (15) calendar days;
5.12.3	Direct the CAD to prepare the necessary adjusting Journal Entry Vouchers (JEVs) to correct the understated beginning and ending balances of RPT and SET Receivables. These adjustments should be recorded in the books of accounts within five (5) working days upon receipt of the corrected summary from the CTO and the completion of the beginning balance reconciliation;
5.12.4	Instruct both the CTO and CAD to implement robust internal controls over the preparation and review of all financial reports, including:
a. Mandatory reconciliation of report summaries with source documents;
b. Verification of formulas and data linkages in spreadsheets;
c. Independent review of computations and data accuracy; and
5.12.5	Ensure that all personnel involved in the preparation and review of financial reports receive adequate and updated training on relevant accounting standards, particularly the NGAS for LGUs, and on proper report generation and reconciliation procedures.

7.9	We recommended that Management:
7.9.1	Direct the concerned officials and employees to immediately liquidate or refund their outstanding cash advances. For long-outstanding amounts, particularly those under the Trust Fund and the stale checks under the General Fund, initiate appropriate administrative and legal actions if necessary to ensure settlement. Set a deadline of thirty (30) calendar days from the receipt of this memorandum for the initial submission of liquidation documents or refunds;
7.9.2	Strengthen the monitoring mechanism for cash advances. Implement a system to track the status of each cash advance, send timely reminders to AOs regarding liquidation deadlines, and promptly follow up on overdue accounts;
7.9.3	Enforce strict compliance with COA Circular No. 97-002 on the liquidation of cash advances. Ensure that all accountable officers are aware of their responsibilities and the consequences of non-compliance, including the withholding of salaries as provided in the Circular;
7.9.4	Conduct a thorough investigation into the untraceable cash advance under the Trust Fund (Buenaventura Bullecer, ₱6,870.00) to determine the circumstances and take appropriate action, including potential write-off, if warranted and properly documented;
7.9.5	Improve coordination between the General Fund and Trust Fund accounting staff, particularly regarding the clearance process for retiring employees, to ensure all accountabilities are settled before final clearance is issued;
7.9.6	Regularly reconcile the subsidiary ledger of cash advances with the general ledger to ensure the accuracy and completeness of records;
7.9.7	Record all financial transactions promptly to ensure that financial reports accurately reflect the LGU's financial position; and
7.9.8	Submit a detailed action plan, outlining the specific steps to be taken to implement these recommendations, including responsible persons and target dates for completion.

10.26	We recommended the Local Chief Executive to take the following actions:
10.26.1	Require the BAC to further investigate or assess the recurring causes of the delay in the supplier’s signing of the PO from the date the NOA was received, prepare a written explanation of their findings, and submit a copy to the Office of the City Auditor;
10.26.2	Based on the findings of their investigation, create and establish internal timelines and procedures for monitoring and routing documents related to Alternative Methods of Procurement to ensure efficiency, competitiveness, and compliance with procurement processes and regulations, and strictly implement them thereafter;
10.26.3	Submit a BAC certification of posting of the RFQ and NOA on PhilGEPS and in conspicuous places, and ensure that the actual posting is properly implemented;
10.26.4	Train personnel to update and upload the required notices and documents to the BAC Gingoog webpage on the LGU-Gingoog website;
10.26.5	Henceforth, submit or attach to the DV proof of posting of the Purchase Order (PO) posting generated from the PhilGEPS website;
10.26.6	Organize and improve the presentation and location of the full disclosure/notice board of the Bids and Awards Committee; and
10.26.7	Remind and guide bidders on the proper completion of the Request for Quotations/Proposals form.

11.10	We recommended to the Local Chief Executive that the personnel in charge of the filling out of relevant and required information should do the following:
11.10.1	Instruct end-users, through the BAC, to follow a standard format and avoid using abbreviation, acronym, or initialism when providing item information (i.e., list the complete item name first, followed by a detailed item specification);
11.10.2	Encourage suppliers/bidders to indicate in the RFQ the following:
- Brand names or "None" if no brand is applicable;
- Numbers, weight, or linear measurement for unit measures that are not universally accepted; and
- The country of manufacture of the items;
11.10.3	Modify the PO template in https://bacsec.com/ to include the following omitted required details:
- Indication of whether the supplier is (i) a manufacturer or exclusive distributor and (ii) registered with the SEC and/or DTI;
- Telephone/fax no. of supplier;
- Mode of procurement; and
- Taxes paid by agency;
11.10.4	Clearly define the place of delivery, date of delivery, delivery terms, and payment terms; and
11.10.5	Ensure that documents are signed and approved only when all required data are complete, to guarantee that the supplier delivers the goods and that the agency processes payments in accordance with the terms and conditions of the agreement.

15.9	We recommended to the Chairman/Vice Chair of the Local School Board the following:
To facilitate in the immediate implementation of Programs, Projects and Activities per budget year;
To coordinate with the Department of Education, City Division Office and possibly assigned a personnel In-Charge for both the LSB and DepEd in the implementation aside from the Chairman/Vice Chair of the Local School Board;
To maximize the utilization of the Special Education Fund to attain the objective for which the funds were appropriated; and
To prepare the budget for SEF Surplus from previous years at an earlier date, as done in CY 2024, in order to implement project on time and will fully provide the needs for quality education in public schools.

16.8	We recommended that the City Accounting Department (CAD) take the following immediate actions:
16.8.1	Remit the full outstanding amount of ₱12,369.21 to the Pag-IBIG Fund immediately to minimize further penalties and ensure the proper crediting of workers' contributions and loan payments;
16.8.2	Conduct a thorough review and reconciliation of all pertinent records, particularly for the periods before 2017 up to March 31, 2023, to accurately identify the covered employees and the corresponding unremitted amounts. This will also help in addressing the lack of information cited by the new SEF in-charge;
16.8.3	Develop and implement a robust system of internal controls to ensure the timely and accurate remittance of all mandatory deductions, including Pag-IBIG contributions and loan payments, in the future. This should include clearly defined responsibilities, processes, and monitoring mechanisms;
16.8.4	Address the identified challenges of voluminous transactions and manpower limitations by exploring potential solutions such as process streamlining, automation where feasible, or requesting additional staffing if justified; and
16.8.5	Submit a detailed plan of action, outlining the steps to be taken to implement these recommendations, including specific timelines for completion.

We have recommended Management the following remedial measures:

a. To require the General Service Officer to prepare an updated Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP) and facilitate the disposal of the unserviceable properties in accordance with Section 379 of RA No. 7160 to avoid further deterioration and to generate additional income from their disposal; 

b. To expedite the disposal of the motor vehicles and construction & heavy equipment which were already appraised by the COA R-10 Technical Services;

c. To investigate the loss of some unserviceable properties such as the two Suzuki Multicab, one 6-wheeler dump truck, one Dongfeng dump truck, and two Daewoo dump trucks; 

d. To require the City Accountant to reconcile the accounting records with the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) of the GSO.

e. To direct the City Accountant to prepare an adjusting entry to derecognize the unserviceable equipment as prescribed under PPSAS No. 17 after IIRUP is duly approved and evaluated by COA.

We recommended that Management:

1. Direct the City Accountant to: 

a. Update its subsidiary records supporting the transactions booked as completed, and those CIP’s for purposes of ascertaining the existence and propriety of accepted projects; 

b. Identify the various projects in all the Construction in Progress (CIP) accounts from the accounting records. Compare this to the listing of projects by year obtained from the office of City Engineering; 

c. Maintain Construction in Progress Ledger Cards (CIPLC) for all projects/assets constructed in accordance with the Government Accounting Manual, Volume II; and

d. Effect the necessary adjusting entry for the transfer of the costs of the completed project from the CIP accounts to Infrastructure Assets and Building and Other Structure Accounts, recording in the Registry of Public Infrastructure and ensure that in recording transactions, the proper accounts are used.

2. Direct the City Engineer to:

a. Coordinate with and submit to the City Accountant a list of all projects undertaken by year with all the needed information for reconciliation purposes and to assist in facilitating/gathering the documents required to adjust the CIP accounts;

b. Locate the files and documents including the final inspections and acceptance of projects completed and ongoing; and

c. Submit its report of the status of the on-going projects/completed, with the corresponding amount, location and period of construction, and also the deficiencies noted on the identified projects with the corresponding recommendations to facilitate the presentation of acceptance reports.

We recommended the City Mayor to:

(a) Instruct the CAO and CGSO, City Assessor’s Office, to gather all records of real properties  consisting of several parcels of land with TCTs, Deed of Sale in favor of the City and Tax Declaration of Property (TDPs) which were not recognized in the books, and facilitate the immediate reconciliation, registration and titling of the lots in the name of the City for their proper recognition in the books of accounts; 

(b) Recognize and take action on the need to revise the Schedule of Market Values through City Ordinance to reflect the appropriate current market value of real properties; 

(c) Consider providing the CGSO and CAO with adequate manpower and training to accomplish their tasks in the inventory taking, maintenance of PPELCs, and reconciliation of PPE book balances and physical inventory report; 

(d) Create the Inventory Committee composed of adequate number of members in order to attain the objectives of COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020; and

(e) Implement the Procedural Guidelines mandated under COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 or the Guidelines and Procedures in the Conduct of PPE, Recognition of PPE Items Found at the Station, and Disposition for Non-Existing/Missing PPE items, for the One-time Cleansing of PPE Account Balances of Government Agencies.

We recommended the City Mayor to:

(a) Formalize the designation/composition of the Inventory Committee thru an Executive Order which gives specific instructions to formulate and employ a strategy in conducting annual physical count taking also into account the Guidelines for the One-Time Cleansing of PPE Account Balances of Government Agencies or COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020; 

(b) 	Require the IC and the CGSO to conduct annual inventory of local roads under the LGU's jurisdiction and come-up with the updated/revised Local Road Inventory and Road Map and Local Road Network Property Card for all roads under the City’s jurisdiction;

(c) 	Instruct the CAO to (i) maintain Local Road Network Ledger Cards and Subsidiary Records for every Road Network; (ii) reconcile the Registry of Public Infrastructure with CGSO; (iii) reclassify the Road Lots totaling 12,368,819.00 erroneously recorded in the Land Account supported with an approved JEV and (iv) disclose the required information on Local Road Networks in the Notes to FS; and 

(d) 	Require the process owners of LRAMS to strictly adhere to the pertinent provisions of COA Circular No. 2015-008 dated November 23, 2015 and COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020.

We recommended that the Management:
Direct the City Accountant and City Treasurer to:
Adhere to the recording requirements of the NGAS for RPT and SET accounts especially in maintenance of Subsidiary Ledgers/Individual Barangay Schedules;
Reconcile its records with the City Treasurer’s Office and make necessary adjustments to correct the balance of RPT Receivable, SET Receivable, Deferred Real Property and Special Education Tax Income;
Conduct periodic/regular reconciliation of records with the CTO in order to ensure the reliability and accuracy of its accounts; and
Upon completion of reconciliation, submit to the audit team the approved JEV together with its supporting documents and Working Papers/Schedules.

We recommended that the City Mayor direct:
The City Treasurer to:
Report all signed checks (issued) whether released or unreleased in the RCI;
Ensure that checks issued are supported with the signatures of the claimants in the check register which will be the basis of transmittal of Disbursement Vouchers to the Accounting Office. Moreover, unsigned “Received by” column of the check register together with the actual check not yet released will be the basis in the preparation of the List of Unreleased Checks for a given period to be submitted to the Accounting Office; and
Strictly monitor liaison officers or authorized representatives so that all paid DVs entrusted to them are submitted at the end of each day;
The City Accountant to:
Record check payments based on RCI and existence of paid DVs taking into consideration the List of Unreleased Checks which includes the cancelled checks;
Submit the 144 DVs totaling ₱14,096,795.84 and DVs for the month of December 2023 and their supporting documents to avoid disallowance.

We have recommended that management require the disbursing officer to update the cashbook accordingly by adopting the following suggested measures: 

1. Discontinue the practice of transferring cash advances from one AO to another as required under Section 4.1.6 of COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997;

2. Update the cashbook daily based on the report of disbursements by the disbursing officer;

3. Closely monitor cash balance by reconciling daily cash on hand with the cash balance in the cashbook to ensure the accuracy and physical existence of cash on hand; and

4. Reconcile the cashbook balance with the accounting records at least quarterly. Make the necessary corrections or adjustments should there be a difference between these two records.

We have recommended that Management:
appropriates funds from the General Fund totalling ₱2,000,000.00 and thereafter direct the Budget Officer and the Accountant for the proper recording of adjustments affecting the transactions listed above, and restitute the said amount to the 20% DF which was depleted due to improper charging thereof;
Henceforth, observe the proper utilization of the 20% DF pursuant to the provisions of DILG and DBM Joint Memorandum Circular No. 1, s. of 2017 to attain the government’s objectives.

